snippet.textDisplay:
How did we get here? HOW DID WE GET HERE????? Jeremy, the moment Lucas sold SW after he had explicitly stated that he had no more plans for SW movies or future stories, is how we got here! Pure unfiltered greed! Gotta make money, if you cant, sell it to someone who wants to try! TFA was a soulless cash in on people nostalgia by basically being A New Hope for the next generation without one iota of creativity or originality in its bones.

Think about everything that was original to TFA and it all sucks. Rey, Finn, Kylo, Phasma, Hux, Snoke. None of these characters had anything about them that was even remotely fleshed out or explored in the initial movie or its sequels. Finn was relegated to plucky comic relief. Rey was a Mary Sue who is given no credible explanation how she can just DO EVERYTHING. Phasma was nothing more than a shiny toy cash in, Hux has been literally ALL OVER THE PLACE from raging psycho, to whipping boy, to now turn coat??? And Snoke? Dude got MERCD without any exploration of who he was in the grand scheme of things.
People trash the TLJ as if it was the sole source of the ST problems but the truth is that from DAY ONE of Disney owning this IP things have become more FUCKED then ever before during the time of the Prequels. TFA had no new ideas, TLJ had no good ideas, and ROS has plainly NO IDEA what it wants to be as the book end to quite possibly one of the most disorganized, poorly planned, directionless film trilogies of ALL TIME!

snippet.textDisplay:
Hey Jeremy, congrats on trending #1 <3 :D and here I shall comment so that thy video will be blessed by the almighty algorithm.

Star Wars films from least liked to favorite: leaving out Solo since I've never seen it

#9 The Phantom Menace. My first impression was hate. I'd waited my whole life to see a Star Wars film in the theatre and all I could think was "this is what you came up with? After 20 years?" I did not like it. I did not get it. And worse, I was surrounded by people singing its praises. My brothers, my fanboy uncle... I was actually told that if I didn't like Episode One, I wasn't a real Star Wars fan. So I turned in my membership card and moved the fuck on. You couldn't pay me to revisit this film.

#8 Attack of the Clones. I've only seen this film once and all I can say is: I didn't hate it. It was 2 hours of a lot of colors and noise on the screen that kept me from falling asleep. I walked out and completely forgot about it for like a decade. But my uncle had a good time and that was the point.

#7 The Last Jedi. This movie felt like a kick in the teeth. Like, it was punishing me for having given a damn in the first place. Please understand: I didn't go in with my own fan theories or specific expectations. I am not a Star Wars fangirl, I didn't give a crap about Rey's parents or who Snoke was. I wasn't bothered by asshole hobo Luke... but I do expect the story to have a point and to be going somewhere. Shocking me just for the sake of subverting my expectations is like an emotional jump scare. Sure, you got my attention for a minute but then you did nothing with it. I kinda felt like they told their story in the laziest way possible. I've spent hours reworking Holdo as a character so that her story with Poe makes more sense and then we might actually give a damn when she sacrifices herself. That storyline didn't have to be shit if the writers were less concerned with shocking the audiences and just focused on a cohesive narrative. Anyway, the movie wasted my time. It did nothing with characters I was excited to see again. I didn't learn anything new about these people that would make me care about their fates. In the end I walked out no longer giving a damn about where this story is going.

#6 Revenge of the Sith. This is the only one of the prequels that I felt even needed to be made. I went in with the lowest expectations. I really didn't care and was only bringing my fanboy uncle so he could have a couple hours away from his kids. And surprise surprise... I actually felt something for these characters. The tragedy managed to hit me. I actually cried when order 66 went up. It was like the Red Wedding: I knew it was gonna happen but seeing it hurt more than I'd expected it to. It's a poorly made movie but I actually got what George was going for this time. I gave a shit.

#5 Rogue One. I'm surprised at how much I ended up liking this. The first half is a disjointed mess, I don't remember most of the characters names and only part of the plot has stuck with me... but just like Wonder Woman nailed the 'no man's land' scene, Rogue One sticks the landing. It got it right where it mattered most. That last act just gets me. It really gives a face to all the rebels who REALLY sacrificed to bring down the empire. No one remembers their names, they're not getting medal ceremonies, they don't get to be legends that children admire... yet arguably they gave more and believed more in the cause than our favorite heroes from the orig trig. And not only that, they gave their lives without any guarantee that it would be worth it. All they had was hope. It gave the 'many bothans' a face. It adds a weight to Luke's winning blow that I never felt before.

#4 Star Wars. Please don't come at me for putting this so low lol Please understand, I was born 3 years after this was released, I didn't get to see it until the mid eighties on tape, and this was AFTER I'd already seen Empire, Jedi, the Ewok adventures and Aliens was my favorite movie in the world. Poor Star Wars barely stood a chance with me by then lol As a kid I thought it was boring and I didn't learn to respect it until adulthood. Now I can appreciate its place in the saga and seeing where these characters I came to love, where they first started, still warms my heart. But I won't lie, I mostly watch it only with Rifftrax playing over it lol Gods, someone's gonna assassinate me

#3 Force Awakens. This is probably sacrilege, having this above the original. What can I say? I had a helluva time with this film. I was an infant when Jedi came out so I never got to experience the orig trig in the theatre. By the time they were re-released in the 90s, I no longer cared (especially with the special additions blegh). I didn't have a good experience with the prequels... seeing TFA in the threatre made me understand finally how my uncle and his peers felt seeing the original Star Wars in '76. He was the fanboy who introduced me to this world. I felt like a 12 year, I wanted to stand up and cheer. I'd waited my whole life to have that Star Wars experience. Yes, the movie is flawed, its world building is a disaster but sometimes it's about getting it right where it really matters so you can get away with getting it wrong where it matters less, ya know?

#2 Jedi. It's cheesy, I know. But it was my first experience with following a great saga to a satisfying conclusion. I loved the characters, was invested in their mission and was very happy that that's where we were leaving them. I know it's silly but I will never not be in the mood to watch it. But it has to be the one with the original ewok song.

#1 Empire, I know... predictable. It's the first film in the saga I ever saw and it just stuck with me. I appreciated it even more once I saw the others and could enjoy it as a part of a larger story. It just does a really good job of making me feel for the fiction. I genuinely care for and feel invested in the characters, their journey, their personal growth. It was my first cliff hanger and I was so thrilled to find out what would happen next.
snippet.textOriginal:
Hey Jeremy, congrats on trending #1 <3 :D and here I shall comment so that thy video will be blessed by the almighty algorithm.

Star Wars films from least liked to favorite: leaving out Solo since I've never seen it

#9 The Phantom Menace. My first impression was hate. I'd waited my whole life to see a Star Wars film in the theatre and all I could think was "this is what you came up with? After 20 years?" I did not like it. I did not get it. And worse, I was surrounded by people singing its praises. My brothers, my fanboy uncle... I was actually told that if I didn't like Episode One, I wasn't a real Star Wars fan. So I turned in my membership card and moved the fuck on. You couldn't pay me to revisit this film.

#8 Attack of the Clones. I've only seen this film once and all I can say is: I didn't hate it. It was 2 hours of a lot of colors and noise on the screen that kept me from falling asleep. I walked out and completely forgot about it for like a decade. But my uncle had a good time and that was the point.

#7 The Last Jedi. This movie felt like a kick in the teeth. Like, it was punishing me for having given a damn in the first place. Please understand: I didn't go in with my own fan theories or specific expectations. I am not a Star Wars fangirl, I didn't give a crap about Rey's parents or who Snoke was. I wasn't bothered by asshole hobo Luke... but I do expect the story to have a point and to be going somewhere. Shocking me just for the sake of subverting my expectations is like an emotional jump scare. Sure, you got my attention for a minute but then you did nothing with it. I kinda felt like they told their story in the laziest way possible. I've spent hours reworking Holdo as a character so that her story with Poe makes more sense and then we might actually give a damn when she sacrifices herself. That storyline didn't have to be shit if the writers were less concerned with shocking the audiences and just focused on a cohesive narrative. Anyway, the movie wasted my time. It did nothing with characters I was excited to see again. I didn't learn anything new about these people that would make me care about their fates. In the end I walked out no longer giving a damn about where this story is going.

#6 Revenge of the Sith. This is the only one of the prequels that I felt even needed to be made. I went in with the lowest expectations. I really didn't care and was only bringing my fanboy uncle so he could have a couple hours away from his kids. And surprise surprise... I actually felt something for these characters. The tragedy managed to hit me. I actually cried when order 66 went up. It was like the Red Wedding: I knew it was gonna happen but seeing it hurt more than I'd expected it to. It's a poorly made movie but I actually got what George was going for this time. I gave a shit. 

#5 Rogue One. I'm surprised at how much I ended up liking this. The first half is a disjointed mess, I don't remember most of the characters names and only part of the plot has stuck with me... but just like Wonder Woman nailed the 'no man's land' scene, Rogue One sticks the landing. It got it right where it mattered most. That last act just gets me. It really gives a face to all the rebels who REALLY sacrificed to bring down the empire. No one remembers their names, they're not getting medal ceremonies, they don't get to be legends that children admire... yet arguably they gave more and believed more in the cause than our favorite heroes from the orig trig. And not only that, they gave their lives without any guarantee that it would be worth it. All they had was hope. It gave the 'many bothans' a face. It adds a weight to Luke's winning blow that I never felt before.

#4 Star Wars. Please don't come at me for putting this so low lol Please understand, I was born 3 years after this was released, I didn't get to see it until the mid eighties on tape, and this was AFTER I'd already seen Empire, Jedi, the Ewok adventures and Aliens was my favorite movie in the world. Poor Star Wars barely stood a chance with me by then lol As a kid I thought it was boring and I didn't learn to respect it until adulthood. Now I can appreciate its place in the saga and seeing where these characters I came to love, where they first started, still warms my heart. But I won't lie, I mostly watch it only with Rifftrax playing over it lol Gods, someone's gonna assassinate me

#3 Force Awakens. This is probably sacrilege, having this above the original. What can I say? I had a helluva time with this film. I was an infant when Jedi came out so I never got to experience the orig trig in the theatre. By the time they were re-released in the 90s, I no longer cared (especially with the special additions blegh). I didn't have a good experience with the prequels... seeing TFA in the threatre made me understand finally how my uncle and his peers felt seeing the original Star Wars in '76. He was the fanboy who introduced me to this world. I felt like a 12 year, I wanted to stand up and cheer. I'd waited my whole life to have that Star Wars experience. Yes, the movie is flawed, its world building is a disaster but sometimes it's about getting it right where it really matters so you can get away with getting it wrong where it matters less, ya know?

#2 Jedi. It's cheesy, I know. But it was my first experience with following a great saga to a satisfying conclusion. I loved the characters, was invested in their mission and was very happy that that's where we were leaving them. I know it's silly but I will never not be in the mood to watch it. But it has to be the one with the original ewok song.

#1 Empire, I know... predictable. It's the first film in the saga I ever saw and it just stuck with me. I appreciated it even more once I saw the others and could enjoy it as a part of a larger story. It just does a really good job of making me feel for the fiction. I genuinely care for and feel invested in the characters, their journey, their personal growth. It was my first cliff hanger and I was so thrilled to find out what would happen next.
